```
SECTION-1

JAVA ARCHITECTURE ‚Äì CLEAN & CONCISE

1. JAVA PROGRAM FLOW
---------------------
1. Write code:  MyClass.java
2. Compile:     javac MyClass.java ‚Üí MyClass.class (bytecode)
3. Execute:     java MyClass ‚Üí JVM runs the bytecode

2. JDK ‚Äì Java Development Kit
------------------------------
üî∏ Full development environment for Java.
üî∏ Includes:
   ‚úî JRE (to run apps)
   ‚úî Development Tools:
      - java    ‚Üí Launches Java apps
      - javac   ‚Üí Compiles Java source to bytecode
      - jdb     ‚Üí Debugger
      - jshell  ‚Üí Interactive shell (Java 9+)

3. JRE ‚Äì Java Runtime Environment
----------------------------------
üî∏ Provides environment to run Java apps.
üî∏ Includes:
   ‚úî JVM
   ‚úî Core Libraries:
      - java.lang   ‚Äì Core classes (String, Math, Object)
      - java.util   ‚Äì Collections, Date, Timer, etc.
      - java.io     ‚Äì File input/output
      - java.net    ‚Äì Networking
      - java.sql    ‚Äì JDBC (Database access)
      - java.time   ‚Äì Date/Time API
      - javax.*     ‚Äì Extended APIs (GUI, Servlet, etc.)

4. JVM ‚Äì Java Virtual Machine
------------------------------
üî∏ Core component that executes compiled bytecode.
üî∏ Key Responsibilities:
   ‚úî Class Loader        ‚Äì Loads .class files into memory
   ‚úî Bytecode Verifier   ‚Äì Ensures type/memory safety
   ‚úî Runtime Data Areas:
      - Heap             ‚Üí Objects & arrays (shared)
      - Stack            ‚Üí Method call frames (per thread)
      - Method Area      ‚Üí Class metadata, static vars
      - PC Register      ‚Üí Current instruction pointer
   ‚úî Execution Engine:
      - Interpreter      ‚Üí Line-by-line execution
      - JIT Compiler     ‚Üí Converts bytecode to native code which is binary (faster)
   ‚úî Garbage Collector   ‚Äì Automatically frees unused memory

ClassLoader:
It is a JVM component that loads Java .class files into memory at runtime.
It loads core classes, extensions, and application classes dynamically from disk or network.
This enables Java‚Äôs dynamic loading and runtime linking of classes.

5. PLATFORM INDEPENDENCE (WORA)
-------------------------------
‚úî Java code compiles to platform-independent bytecode(binary).
‚úî JVMs on different OSes interpret same bytecode.
‚úî Motto: "Write Once, Run Anywhere"

some point:

 Compiler:
 Translates entire source code into machine code (binary) before execution.
- Output is an executable file (.class in Java bytecode).
-Full translation before execution, fast execution.
- Interpreter: On-the-fly translation during execution, slower.
- JIT Compiler: Runtime compilation of bytecode to native code for faster execution in JVM.


NOTE:
- javac produces bytecode saved on disk (.class files).
- JVM loads bytecode and either interprets it or uses JIT to compile hot code to native machine code.
- Native machine code produced by JIT runs directly on your CPU for speed.

==========================================================================
IMPORTANT JAVA NOTES TO REMEMBER
=================================

1. COMPILATION & FILE STRUCTURE
-------------------------------
‚úî .java ‚Üí Source code file
‚úî .class ‚Üí Bytecode file (created after compilation)
‚úî File name must match public class name (case-sensitive)
‚úî Only one public class allowed per file

2. PACKAGE & DIRECTORY RULE
----------------------------
‚úî Package name must match folder structure
   e.g., package com.example ‚Üí File path: /com/example/ClassName.java
‚úî Compile with: javac -d . MyClass.java   (creates folders automatically)

3. CLASSLOADER BEHAVIOR
------------------------
‚úî Bootstrap ClassLoader ‚Äì Loads core Java classes (java.lang, etc.)
‚úî Application ClassLoader ‚Äì Loadscustom classes which we build in code.

4. MAIN METHOD SYNTAX
----------------------
‚úî Must be:
   `public static void main(String[] args)`
‚úî `String[] args` can be written as `String args[]`
You must declare main with String[] args for the JVM to find it.

5. ENTRY POINT RULE
--------------------
‚úî Without `main()`, app won‚Äôt run unless it's a library or framework (e.g., Spring Boot)

Regular Java apps need public static void main(String[] args) to run.

Spring Boot apps have a main method in the framework starter, so you don‚Äôt write it yourself every time.
@SpringBootApplication

6. CASE SENSITIVITY
--------------------
‚úî Java is **case-sensitive**.
‚úî `Main`, `main`, `String`, `string` are all treated differently.

7. UNICODE SUPPORT
-------------------
‚úî Java source code and string literals are Unicode compliant (supports all languages)

8. CLASS VS OBJECT
-------------------
‚úî Class ‚Äì Blueprint
‚úî Object ‚Äì Instance of a class created using `new`

9. ACCESS MODIFIERS
--------------------
‚úî public       ‚Äì Visible everywhere
‚úî private      ‚Äì Only within same class
‚úî protected    ‚Äì Same package + subclasses
‚úî default      ‚Äì Package-private (no modifier)

10. STATIC VS INSTANCE
-----------------------
‚úî static ‚Äì Belongs to class, loaded once
‚úî instance ‚Äì Belongs to object

11. FINAL KEYWORD
------------------
‚úî final class     ‚Äì Cannot be extended
‚úî final method    ‚Äì Cannot be overridden
‚úî final variable  ‚Äì Constant, value can't change

12. THIS vs SUPER
------------------
‚úî this ‚Äì Refers to current class instance
‚úî super ‚Äì Refers to parent class

13. DEFAULT VALUES
-------------------
‚úî int ‚Üí 0, double ‚Üí 0.0, boolean ‚Üí false, object ‚Üí null

14. MEMORY AREAS (JVM)
-----------------------
‚úî Heap        ‚Äì Objects
‚úî Stack       ‚Äì Method calls & local vars
‚úî Method Area ‚Äì Class structure info
‚úî GC clears only unused heap objects

15. GARBAGE COLLECTION
-----------------------
‚úî Automatic memory cleanup (no need to manually free)
‚úî Object eligible for GC when no reference points to it



